JavaScript is a popular programming language that is used to create dynamic and interactive web applications. It is a scripting language that is inserted into HTML pages, and it is also used to build mobile and desktop apps as well. It has been around for almost 25 years so it’s known and fairly understood by many developers. JavaScript is interpreted by a program called the JavaScript engine, which converts JavaScript code into machine-level code that is executed on the web browser.
Typescript on the other hand is a syntactic superset of JavaScript. It has additional features that extend JavaScript’s syntax. Typescript provides access to type information, error checking, and (limited) type inference at compile time. It also integrates nicely with Angular, React, and many other libraries and frameworks. Typescript is a typed language, which means that every variable, function, and class must be declared with a specific type. This helps reduce errors and improve code quality. Typescript supports the same JavaScript syntax as the open web, however its compilers ensure that all code meets a very specific structure known as type definitions which give additional flexibility and assurance for developer applications.
Typescript has been steadily gaining popularity in recent years due to its ability to provide modern development capabilities while still being backward compatible with JavaScript. Overall, it’s a language with a bright future.

1) life exists elsewhere in the galaxy,
2) life forms intelligent if it develops an industrial civilization, and
